<paragraph id="8B855F61FFA5FFA6FF57D6F33480725B" blockId="5.[125,1172,1465,1683]" lastBlockId="6.[138,1185,137,545]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="405" pageId="5" pageNumber="404">
Leg 1 (
<figureCitation id="130143E4FFA5FFA5FF30D6F3343F75AB" box="[255,373,1465,1489]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1338,1357]" captionTargetBox="[253,1041,138,1278]" captionTargetId="figure-98@5.[250,1048,133,1303]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Caligus arii Bassett-Smith, adult female. (A) Leg 1, with tip shown in ventral view (upper insertion) and dorsal view (lower insertion); (B) leg 2; (C) leg 3; (D) leg 4; (E) left half of anal somite and caudal ramus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4582145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4582145/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="404">Figure 2A</figureCitation>
) protopod with long, plumose, outer seta and another small, plumose, inner seta in addition to a patch of spinules on ventral surface; vestigial endopod fringed with setules around distal region; first segment of exopod with row of setules on posterior edge and short spiniform seta at outer distal corner; outer three of four terminal elements on last segment of exopod with sharply pointed, slender tip and hyaline membrane on posterior margin, middle two elements with long accessory process and element four with a small, spiniform seta. Leg 2 (
<figureCitation id="130143E4FFA5FFA5FCC7D531363776E9" box="[776,893,1659,1683]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1338,1357]" captionTargetBox="[253,1041,138,1278]" captionTargetId="figure-98@5.[250,1048,133,1303]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Caligus arii Bassett-Smith, adult female. (A) Leg 1, with tip shown in ventral view (upper insertion) and dorsal view (lower insertion); (B) leg 2; (C) leg 3; (D) leg 4; (E) left half of anal somite and caudal ramus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4582145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4582145/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="404">Figure 2B</figureCitation>
) coxa small, with large plumose inner seta on posterior edge and setule-bearing papilla on ventral surface; basis with simple, outer seta and medial papilla bearing long setule; both outer and medial edges of protopod fringed with large marginal membrane; similar membrane on outer margin of elongated, proximal segment of exopod; basal segment of endopod with small distolateral membrane, but terminal two segments bearing rows of setules on outer surface. Leg 3 (
<figureCitation id="130143E4FFA6FFA6FE8DD26334F3713B" box="[322,441,297,321]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1338,1357]" captionTargetBox="[253,1041,138,1278]" captionTargetId="figure-98@5.[250,1048,133,1303]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Caligus arii Bassett-Smith, adult female. (A) Leg 1, with tip shown in ventral view (upper insertion) and dorsal view (lower insertion); (B) leg 2; (C) leg 3; (D) leg 4; (E) left half of anal somite and caudal ramus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4582145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4582145/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Figure 2C</figureCitation>
) protopod (apron) with short, outer and long, inner seta; large marginal membrane on outer edge and another marginal membrane on posterior edge of basis inner to velum; setule-bearing papilla on basis near both ends of this posterior membrane; and a patch of spinules on lateral edge of ventral surface of protopod. Leg 4 (
<figureCitation id="130143E4FFA6FFA6FF5DD2E3344171BB" box="[146,267,425,449]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1338,1357]" captionTargetBox="[253,1041,138,1278]" captionTargetId="figure-98@5.[250,1048,133,1303]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Caligus arii Bassett-Smith, adult female. (A) Leg 1, with tip shown in ventral view (upper insertion) and dorsal view (lower insertion); (B) leg 2; (C) leg 3; (D) leg 4; (E) left half of anal somite and caudal ramus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4582145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4582145/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Figure 2D</figureCitation>
) protopod with small, plumose, outer seta; pectens on three exopodal segments at insertion of each of five outer spines. Leg 5 (inserted drawing in 
<figureCitation id="130143E4FFA6FFA6FBEAD28331D2719B" box="[1061,1176,457,481]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[138,198,1244,1263]" captionTargetBox="[262,1058,133,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-56@4.[262,1060,133,1208]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. Caligus arii Bassett-Smith, adult female. (A) Habitus, dorsal; (B) antennule; (C) antenna, postantennal process, and maxillule; (D) mandible; (E) maxilla; (F) maxilliped; (G) sternal furca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4582141" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4582141/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
) represented by three small, plumose setae on a protuberance located on posterolateral margin of genital complex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B855F61FFA6FFA6FF45D11035A37208" blockId="6.[138,233,602,626]" box="[138,233,602,626]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FF45D11035A37208" box="[138,233,602,626]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B855F61FFA6FFA6FF45D1C137EB73BE" blockId="6.[138,1185,651,1093]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">
his is the first record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FE78D1C1374972D9" authorityName="Bassett-Smith" authorityYear="1898" box="[439,515,651,675]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arii">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FE78D1C1374972D9" box="[439,515,651,675]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">C. arii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from a host other than a marine catfish. However, we consider the carrier of our 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FE0FD1E1374272B9" authorityName="Bassett-Smith" authorityYear="1898" box="[448,520,683,707]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arii">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FE0FD1E1374272B9" box="[448,520,683,707]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">C. arii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a largehead hairtail, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FCCBD1E1310F72B9" authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[772,1093,683,707]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichiuridae" genus="Trichiurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lepturus">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FCCBD1E1368572B9" box="[772,975,683,707]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Trichiurus lepturus</emphasis>
Linnaeus
</taxonomicName>
, to be a fortuitous host, because we have examined in the past 10 years no fewer than 1000 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FB48D18635977379" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichiuridae" genus="Trichiurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lepturus">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FB48D18635977379" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">T. lepturus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and only one female 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FE3AD1A1370B7379" authorityName="Bassett-Smith" authorityYear="1898" box="[501,577,747,771]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arii">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FE3AD1A1370B7379" box="[501,577,747,771]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">C. arii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recovered from them. Nevertheless, our specimen from 
<collectingCountry id="F32D1FF1FFA6FFA6FE85D04134EB7359" box="[330,417,779,803]" name="Taiwan" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
fits very well with the description of the 
<typeStatus id="5481E1C3FFA6FFA6FC7CD04131407359" box="[947,1034,779,803]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">syntype</typeStatus>
(reg. no. is 98.12.2.9, in the Natural History Museum, London) given by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB2290FFA6FFA6FC73D06131117339" author="Pillai NK" box="[956,1115,811,835]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" pagination="149 - 174" refId="ref6328" refString="Pillai NK. 1969. Notes on some copepod parasites in the collection of the British Museum (N. H.), London. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India 11: 149 - 174." type="journal article" year="1969">Pillai (1969)</bibRefCitation>
. The characteristic features of the present species are: (1) two-segmented, long abdomen with tiny anal segment; (2) minute caudal ramus attaching subterminally to anal segment; (3) absence of postantennal process; (4) maxilliped with slender corpus; and (5) reduced proximal segment and spine on leg 3 exopod.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B855F61FFA6FFA6FF6AD08737EA743F" blockId="6.[138,1185,651,1093]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">
If 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB2290FFA6FFA6FF70D08734E3739F" author="Kirtisinghe P" box="[191,425,973,997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" pagination="45 - 132" refId="ref6206" refString="Kirtisinghe P. 1964. A review of the parasitic copepods of fish recorded from Ceylon, with description of additional forms. Bulletin of the Fisheries Research Station, Ceylon 17: 45 - 132." type="journal article" year="1964">Kirtisinghe’s (1964)</bibRefCitation>
proposal to move 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB2290FFA6FFA6FD4ED0873603739F" author="Barnard KH" box="[641,841,973,997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" pagination="223 - 312" refId="ref6072" refString="Barnard KH. 1955. South African parasitic Copepoda. Annals of the South African Museum 41: 223 - 312." type="journal article" year="1955">Barnard’s (1955)</bibRefCitation>
‘‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FCAFD0873694739F" authorityName="Bassett-Smith" authorityYear="1898" box="[864,990,973,997]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arii">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FCAFD0873694739F" box="[864,990,973,997]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Caligus arii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
B-S.’’ to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FB9FD0873480747F" authority="van Beneden, 1892" authorityName="van Beneden" authorityYear="1892" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dakari">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FB9FD087359B747F" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Caligus dakari</emphasis>
van Beneden, 1892
</taxonomicName>
is correct, then, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FD6CD0A737BB747F" authorityName="Bassett-Smith" authorityYear="1898" box="[675,753,1005,1029]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arii">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FD6CD0A737BB747F" box="[675,753,1005,1029]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">C. arii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is so far known only from 
<collectingCountry id="F32D1FF1FFA6FFA6FB81D0A731EB747F" box="[1102,1185,1005,1029]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">Ceylon</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB2290FFA6FFA6FF5DD7473433745F" author="Bassett-Smith PW" box="[146,377,1037,1061]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" pagination="77 - 98" refId="ref6094" refString="Bassett-Smith PW. 1898. Further new parasitic copepods found on fish in the Indo-tropical region. Annals and Magazine of Natural History (Series 7) 2: 77 - 98." type="journal article" year="1898">Bassett-Smith 1898</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F32D1FF1FFA6FFA6FE74D74734BD745F" box="[443,503,1037,1061]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">India</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB2290FFA6FFA6FDCAD74737C3745F" author="Pillai NK" box="[517,649,1037,1061]" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" pagination="68 - 96" refId="ref6279" refString="Pillai NK. 1963. Copepods parasitic on south Indian fishes-family Caligidae. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India 5: 68 - 96." type="journal article" year="1963">Pillai 1963</bibRefCitation>
). This means that the present report is the first record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A24E2FFA6FFA6FF32D767340C743F" authorityName="Bassett-Smith" authorityYear="1898" box="[253,326,1069,1093]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="6" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arii">
<emphasis id="B94E8373FFA6FFA6FF32D767340C743F" box="[253,326,1069,1093]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="405">C. arii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
outside of the Indian Ocean.
</paragraph>
